Requirement

3D PCAsample A 3D PCA plot like the one in the article, showing the relationships between different sample groups.

Figure 1 Different immune phenotypes between glioma grades (A) Principal components analysis of immune-related genes between glioblastoma (GBM) and lower grade glioma (LGG).

Figure 2 An 8-gene local immune signature for patients with glioblastoma (GBM) (C) Distribution of samples based on the whole genome expression data. (D) High- and low-risk patients distributed on 2 sides based on the immune system process gene set.

https://n.neurology.org/content/86/24/2226 Source: https://n.neurology.org/content/86/24/2226

Application Scenarios

PCAbatch effect Scenario 1: PCA is generally used for quality control, providing an overall assessment of the batch effect of sequencing data.

Figure 2 CDCwhole genome expression dataDimmune-related gene sets clearly divided patients into 2 sections, indicating their remarkable difference in immune phenotype. Figure 1 Aimmune-related gene set PCAindicating distinct immune phenotypes among histologic grades Scenario 2: Showing differences in specific genes between groups. Compare Figures 2 C and D. C uses whole genome expression data, lumping all samples together. D, using immune-related gene sets, clearly divides patients into two sections, indicating their remarkable differences in immune phenotype. Similarly, Figure 1 A uses the immune-related gene set for PCA, indicating distinct immune phenotypes among histologic grades.

Input File

easy_inputPCA If your data is already organized in easy_input format, skip directly to PCA Analysis.

Download the Input File

CGGA.mRNA_array_301_gene_level.20191128.txtsampleCGGAExpression Data (gene level) Gene expression matrix, CGGA.mRNA_array_301_gene_level.20191128.txt, one gene per row, one sample per column. Download Expression Data (gene level) from CGGA and unzip it.

CGGA.mRNA_array_301_clinical.20191128.txtCGGA_IDGradeGradeLGGGBMCGGAClinical Data Grouping information, CGGA.mRNA_array_301_clinical.20191128.txt, contains at least two columns: CGGA_ID and Grade. Here, Grade is used to group LGG and GBM. Download Clinical Data from CGGA and unzip it.

MSigDB Download immune-related genes from MSigDB. This method can also be used to download genes for other pathways of interest:

  • immune system process, M13664IMMUNE_SYSTEM_PROCESS_M13664.txt
  • immune response, M19817IMMUNE_RESPONSE_M19817.txt
  • immune system process, M13664 gene set, renamed IMMUNE_SYSTEM_PROCESS_M13664.txt;
  • [immune response, The gene set M19817 has been renamed to IMMUNE_RESPONSE_M19817.txt.

Read group information

CGGA_IDGrade Use two columns: CGGA_ID and Grade

clinical_data <- read.table("CGGA.mRNA_array_301_clinical.20191128.txt", header=T, sep="\t")
clinical_data <- clinical_data[!is.na(clinical_data$Grade), ]
clinical_data[1,]
##   CGGA_ID TCGA_subtypes PRS_type Histology  Grade Gender Age  OS Censor
## 1 CGGA_11     Classical  Primary       GBM WHO IV Female  57 155      1
##   Radio_status Chemo_status IDH_mutation_status X1p19q_Codeletion_status
## 1            1            0            Wildtype                     <NA>
table(clinical_data$Grade)
## 
##  WHO II WHO III  WHO IV 
##     117      57     124
# LGGGradeWHO IIWHO IIILGG
# Get the LGG sample name. WHO II and WHO III in Grade are defined as LGG.
lgg_sample <- as.character(subset(clinical_data, Grade %in% c("WHO II", "WHO III"))[, "CGGA_ID"])
lgg_sample <- lgg_sample[lgg_sample %in% colnames(exp_data)]
write.table(lgg_sample, "easy_input_group1.txt", quote = F, row.names = F)

# GBMGradeWHO IVLGG
# Get the GBM sample name. WHO IV in Grade is defined as LGG.
gbm_sample <- as.character(subset(clinical_data, Grade %in% c("WHO IV"))[, "CGGA_ID"])
gbm_sample <- gbm_sample[gbm_sample %in% colnames(exp_data)]
write.table(gbm_sample, "easy_input_group2.txt", quote = F, row.names = F)

Read genes involved in a specific pathway

#  # Read the gene collection
immune_response <- as.character(read.table("IMMUNE_RESPONSE_M19817.txt", skip=2)[, 1])
immune_system_process <- as.character(read.table("IMMUNE_SYSTEM_PROCESS_M13664.txt", skip=2)[, 1])
immune_genes <- unique(c(immune_response, immune_system_process))
immune_genes <- immune_genes[immune_genes %in% rownames(exp_data)]

#  # Obtain gene expression profiles of interest
immune_data <- exp_data[immune_genes, c(lgg_sample, gbm_sample)]
immune_data[1:5, 1:5]
##        CGGA_253 CGGA_256 CGGA_258 CGGA_267 CGGA_271

PCA

PCA analysis

#  # Read gene expression matrix
immune_data <- read.csv("easy_input_expr.csv", row.names = 1)
immune_data[1:3,1:3]
##        CGGA_253 CGGA_256 CGGA_258
## AIM2        1.4      0.1      1.1
## ANXA11     -0.1      0.8      0.3
## APLN        0.3      0.0      0.5
dim(immune_data)
## [1] 311 297
# PCA # Perform PCA
pca <- prcomp(t(immune_data))

Start plotting

# sample ID
# Sample IDs for the two groups
lgg_sample <- read.table("easy_input_group1.txt", header = T)$x
gbm_sample <- read.table("easy_input_group2.txt", header = T)$x

# 
# Prepare the colors
lgg_color <- rep("yellow", length(lgg_sample))
names(lgg_color) <- lgg_sample
gbm_color <- rep("red", length(gbm_sample))
names(gbm_color) <- gbm_sample
groups <- c(lgg_color, gbm_color)

Run the following code and a drawing window will pop up. Drag the mouse to the desired angle and size, then save the image.

# 3d PCA
# 3D PCA plot
plot3d(pca$x[,1:3], #  # Take the first three principal components
       xlab="Comp.1", ylab="Comp.2", zlab="Comp.3", 
       col=groups, # groups # Fill color by group
       type="s", # 'p' for points, 's' for spheres, 'l' for lines, 'h' for line segments 
# Draw spheres, 'p' for points, 's' for spheres, 'l' for lines, 'h' for line segments
       size=1, # # Size of the spheres
       lwd=2, box=T)
# (png)
#rgl.snapshot("PCA.png")
# Save (Currently only saves to png)
#rgl.snapshot("PCA.png")

3D Sometimes, we want to display multiple 3D graphs in the same article from the same angle. To do this, save the angle and load it each time you draw.

#3D
# Manually adjust the 3D shape's position and obtain the angle
myMatrix <- par3d()
userMatrix <- myMatrix$userMatrix
windowRect <- myMatrix$windowRect
# 
# Save the angle to a file
#save(userMatrix, windowRect, file = "mypar3d.RData")

# 
# Load the previously adjusted angle
(load("mypar3d.RData"))

3Dlegend Since this is a 3D graph, youll need to adjust the angle in the pop-up window. Add the legend after adjusting the angle.

Illustrator You can also manually add the legend using software like Illustrator for greater flexibility.

legend3d("topright", # legend # Legend position
         legend = c("LGG (n=173)", "GBM (n=124)"), #  # Handwritten text
         bty = "n", #  # No border
         cex = 2, #  # Text size
         pch = 16, #  # Circle
         col = c("yellow", "red")) #  # Colors consistent with the image
